727582f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Union Street, Queens, NY
727582f-a.text:

P. L. Sperr  August 24, 1935

727583f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Union Street, Queens, NY
727583f-a.text:
Northern Boul., south side, bctween Union St. (right), and Bowne St. (left), showing the Aspinwall house, erected in 1760 b, John Aspinwall. Some of the occupants were Jos. T. Darling, 1860-1873; W. H. Secor, 1891; Dr. Bloodgood, 1846; Paul De Lacy Lieberman, 1897; and one Halleran who was the owner in 1925. The City Club Auide states that this house was used by the British as their headquarters during the Revolutionary War.
Views: 1-2 1922
View: 3 March 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection,

727586f-a.folder: Northern Boulevard & Union Street, Queens, NY
727586f-a.text:
Northern Boulevard, from Union Street to Bowne Street. The two houses facing the Boulevard and adjoining the corner were the property of T. Dowling in 1891. The frame structure partially seen on Union Street was the property of the Queens County Savings Bank of 1891.
August 24, 1935.
P. L. Sperr.
